    medications: [],
    pearls: ["ABO HDFN is the most common form but is usually mild because A and B antigens are not fully developed on fetal RBCs", "Anti-Kell causes HDFN by suppressing fetal erythropoiesis rather than hemolysis so reticulocyte counts may be misleadingly low", "RhIG prevents anti-D formation but cannot help if the mother is already sensitized with anti-D antibodies"],
    quiz: [{"question": "A Kleihauer-Betke test is performed to determine:", "options": ["Maternal blood type", "The volume of fetal-maternal hemorrhage to calculate the appropriate dose of RhIG", "Fetal hemoglobin electrophoresis pattern", "Maternal antibody titer"], "correctIndex": 1, "rationale": "KB acid elution test: quantifies fetal RBCs in maternal circulation. Fetal hemoglobin (HbF) resists acid elution while adult HbA is eluted. Percentage of fetal cells × maternal blood volume = FMH volume. Standard RhIG dose (300 μg) covers 30 mL fetal blood. Additional doses calculated based on FMH volume."}]
