    cellular: "Clinical enzymology measures enzyme activities in serum to detect tissue damage, since enzymes are released into the bloodstream when cells are injured or destroyed. Liver enzymes: ALT (alanine aminotransferase, most liver-specific), AST (aspartate aminotransferase, liver and muscle), ALP (alkaline phosphatase, liver and bone — GGT differentiates source), GGT (gamma-glutamyl transferase, most sensitive for hepatobiliary disease and alcohol use). Hepatocellular pattern: ALT/AST markedly elevated with relatively normal ALP. Cholestatic pattern: ALP/GGT markedly elevated with mild transaminase elevation. AST:ALT ratio >2:1 suggests alcoholic liver disease (pyridoxal phosphate deficiency reduces ALT more than AST). Cardiac: troponin I/T (most cardiac-specific — 99th percentile URL for MI diagnosis), CK-MB (relative index distinguishes cardiac from skeletal source). Pancreatic: lipase (more specific than amylase for acute pancreatitis), amylase (also elevated in salivary gland disease, macroamylasemia). Bone: bone-specific ALP, osteocalcin. Muscle: CK-MM (skeletal), aldolase.",
