    cellular: "Clinical parasitology involves identification of protozoa and helminths in clinical specimens. Protozoa: single-celled organisms classified by motility — amoebae (Entamoeba histolytica: flask-shaped ulcers, ingested RBCs in trophozoites), flagellates (Giardia lamblia: pear-shaped trophozoite with 'falling leaf' motility, ventral sucking disk), ciliates (Balantidium coli), and sporozoa (Plasmodium, Cryptosporidium, Toxoplasma). Helminths: multicellular worms — nematodes (roundworms: Ascaris, hookworm, Enterobius), cestodes (tapeworms: Taenia, Diphyllobothrium), trematodes (flukes: Schistosoma). Diagnostic methods: ova and parasite (O&P) examination (direct wet mount, concentrated preparation, permanent stained smear using trichrome or iron hematoxylin), modified acid-fast stain for Cryptosporidium and Cyclospora, thick and thin blood smears for malaria/Babesia, pinworm paddle (Scotch tape test) for Enterobius, antigen detection tests (Giardia, Cryptosporidium), and molecular testing (PCR panels for gastrointestinal parasites).",
